d","1409–Male":"1409–Deceased","1410–1434":"1410–1434","1415–Male":"1415–Deceased","1417–Female":"1417–Deceased","1419–Female":"1419–Deceased","1421–Female":"1421–Deceased","1423–Female":"1423–Deceased","1351–Male":"1351–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1423":"1423","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1452":"1452","1409":"1409","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bolton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in northern England named Bolton (Lancashire, Northumberland, Westmorland, and Yorkshire) or from Boulton in Derbyshire and East Lothian in Scotland, from Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Boulton","meanings":["English: variant of   Bolton  ."]},{"name":"Bold","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>bold</i> ‘dwelling-house’ (Old English <i>bold</i> the West Midland and northwestern form of Old English <i>bōthl</i>, <i>bōtl</i>), especially in the sense ‘castle or manor house’ for someone who lived or worked at the main house, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, for example Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel De Bolton was born in 1374, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Bolton IV, was 23 and her mother, Catherine of Yorkshire, was 14. She married John Lister in 1395, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 6 sons and 4 daughters. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1374–Deceased":"1374–Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1370–1434":"1370–1434","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–1452":"1400–1452","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1409–Male":"1409–Surnud","1410–1434":"1410–1434","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1421–Female":"1421–Surnud","1423–Female":"1423–Surnud","1351–Male":"1351–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1423":"1423","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1452":"1452","1409":"1409","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"